Introduction¶

We will have to explore and look for some answers to questions such how many of the patients attend and how many don't show up. We will also have to check all the factors we have and try to figure out each of their effect on the show status and then combine some of them to see if combined factors may affect the show status in a different way.

Investigating the effect of some factors on the show status.¶

Does age affect the attendance?

In [67]:
#defining a function to check different factors affecting the show status

def show_status(p_show, p_no_show, factor_): # # factor_ variable should be the name of the column in string format
   
    plt.figure(figsize=[16,6])

    p_show[factor_].hist(alpha= .5, color= 'blue', label= 'attendance')
    p_no_show[factor_].hist(alpha= .5, color= 'red', label= 'absence')
    
    plt.title(' Comparing Attendance With {}'.format(factor_), size= 18)
    plt.xlabel(factor_, size= 14)
    plt.ylabel('Number Of Patients', size= 14)
    plt.legend();

show_status(p_show, p_no_show,'Age')

We can see from this histogram that the age of the patients who attend their apointments the most are from 1-12 then ages from aroud 47-58. The least showings are patients above 68 years old.

Does gender affect the attendance?

In [68]:
def show_status_vc(p_show, p_no_show, factor_): #factor_ variable should be the name of the column in string format
    
    plt.figure(figsize=[16,6])

    p_show[factor_].value_counts().plot(kind= 'bar', alpha= .5, color= 'blue', label= 'Attendance')
    p_no_show[factor_].value_counts().plot(kind= 'bar', alpha= .5, color= 'red', label= 'Absence')
    
    plt.title(' Comparing Attendance With {}'.format(factor_), size= 18)
    plt.xlabel(factor_, size= 14)
    plt.ylabel('Number Of Patients', size= 14)
    plt.legend();

show_status_vc(p_show, p_no_show,'Gender')

looks like the Gender doesn't affect the show status since the ratio for both genders looks the same, around 2:1 attendance to absence.

Does receiving SMS affects the attendance?

In [69]:
show_status_vc(p_show, p_no_show,'SMS_received')

as we can see most of the patients who attended didn't recieve text messages, and half the patients who recieved text messages were absent.

In [64]:
# defining a funtcion to plot the attendance related to a mean Age of certain disease
def mean_2_factors(p_show, p_no_show, factor_1, factor_2 ): # factor_1 and factor_2 variables should be the name of the columns in string format
    
    plt.figure(figsize=[16,6])

    p_show.groupby([factor_1]).mean(numeric_only=True )[factor_2].plot(kind= 'bar', alpha= .7, color= 'blue', label= 'attendance')
    p_no_show.groupby([factor_1]).mean(numeric_only=True)[factor_2].plot(kind= 'bar', alpha= .7, color= 'red', label= 'absence')
    
    plt.title(' Comparing Attendance With {} & {}'.format(factor_1, factor_2), size= 18)
    plt.xlabel('{}'.format(factor_1), size= 14)
    plt.ylabel('Mean {}'.format(factor_2), size= 14)
    plt.legend();

What's the effect of age with patients having dabetes?

Conclusions¶

We can see that more patients attended without receiving SMS and most who received it didn't attend, which means something is wrong with SMS service. We can also see that the Age and neighbourhoods has great impact on the show status. The patients who attend their apointments the most are from 1-12 years old, then ages from aroud 47-58 years old, and the least showings are patients above 68 years old. ILHAS OCEANICAS DE TRINDADE has the most attendancy. Also, patients from specific neibourhoods are affected by age and SMS. Finally, we foun no clear relationship between the show status and gender, Hypertension, Diabetes, Scholarship, Alchohol or Handcap.
